{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Migrations are applied in ascending numeric order determined by the filename prefix.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The failure boundary is between file discovery/parsing/sorting and migration execution order. A unit test of only the sort helper can miss real wiring bugs (e.g., unsorted directory results passed through incorrectly). No OS/external-system behavior beyond local filesystem + DB wiring is required.","test_description":"Create a test migrations directory with out-of-order filenames (e.g., 001, 010, 002), run the migration runner against a local test DB, and have each migration append its version into an audit table. Assert recorded execution order is 001 -> 002 -> 010.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.35,"Integration":0.6,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"A migration that has already been applied is not re-executed on a subsequent run.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This behavior depends on interaction between migration execution and persisted `_migrations` metadata across runs. Mocking DB metadata reads/writes can hide real query/table-state bugs, so multiple modules with a real local DB boundary are needed.","test_description":"Run the runner once with a migration that inserts a sentinel row, then run it again against the same DB. Assert sentinel effect appears only once and `_migrations` contains a single record for that migration version.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.8,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"When a migration statement fails, its changes are rolled back automatically and no further migrations in the same run are attempted.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Rollback correctness is at the runner+database transaction boundary; mocks often cannot faithfully reproduce transactional rollback semantics and stop-on-failure behavior together. It does not require external API or multi-process orchestration.","test_description":"Use three migrations: first performs a valid write, second performs one valid write then a failing statement, third performs another write. Run once and assert: changes from second are fully rolled back, third was not applied, and `_migrations` records only the first migration.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.75,"System":0.2,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"When two instances of the runner start at the same time against the same database, each migration is applied exactly once across both instances.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"The failure boundary is true cross-process concurrency and DB locking/uniqueness behavior. In-process mocks or single-process integration tests can miss race conditions that appear only with simultaneous runner processes.","test_description":"Launch two separate runner processes concurrently against the same test Postgres instance and the same migrations directory. After both exit, assert each migration’s side effects exist exactly once and `_migrations` has exactly one row per migration version.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.0,"Integration":0.1,"System":0.9,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"On the very first run against a fresh database, the `_migrations` table is created before any migration file is applied.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This is bootstrap sequencing across modules (metadata-table init + migration apply) with DB schema state. A unit test of init logic alone can miss ordering bugs in the orchestrator. No external-network or agentic dependency is involved.","test_description":"Against a fresh DB, include a first migration that references `_migrations` existence indirectly (or capture DB state transitions via hooks/logging). Run runner and assert `_migrations` exists and is initialized before first migration is recorded/applied, with run succeeding on empty initial schema.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.15,"Integration":0.8,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}}]}
